        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to map G351.77 with a mosaic of 149 fields and an angular resolution of 1.4 arcsec. 

Sensitivity estimate: 
From the 8 micron Spitzer image we estimate a size of ~3.5 arcsec in width and 24 arcsec in length for the sub-filaments we want to investigate.  
We aim at 10 mJy/beam with a spectral resolution of 0.5 km/s, which is required to resolve typical linewidths of 3-5 km/s.
The 10 mJy/beam sensitivity is needed to detect HCO+ and HNC in the sub-filaments: the weakest MOPRA HNC and HCO+ emission in an isolated sub-filament is  0.25K (2.2 Jy/beam). 43 ALMA beams (1.4 arcsec) are needed to cover a sub-filament of 3.5 arcsec times 24 arcsec area. Assuming a uniform distribution of the 2.2 Jy/beam flux over this area, we need a sensitivity of 10 mJy/beam to detect the line at a 5 sigma level. 

This is a very conservative estimate since we do expect HNC and HCO+ to be more peaked. Emission along the ridge is much stronger than that in the sub-filaments and our conservative estimate will guarantee a much higher signal-to-noise ratio along the ridge. 

The corresponding continuum sensitivity, assuming line contamination up to 50% (at least towards the brightest IRAS 17233-3606 source) is 0.1 mJy/beam, which guarantees us a sensitivity to 0.02M solar masses assuming that all emission comes from dust (Schnee &amp; Carpenter 2009).





</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Typical line widths in the sub-filaments are ~1.5-3 km/s. We require a spectral resolution of ~0.1-0.2 in some bands because we need a high precision to study the velocity field of the main  ridge where lines are much stronger than the 50 mJy/beam flux used in the sensitivity estimate.

Spectral setup: 

We aim to cover HNC(1-0), HCO+(1-0), H13CO+(1-0), HN13C(1-0) and SiO(2-1) to study kinematics of the sub-filaments (HNC(1-0), HCO+(1-0)), the kinematics of the ridge and possible global collapse  (HCO+(1-0), H13CO+(1-0), HN13C(1-0)), and detect down to sub-solar masses YSOs (continuum) and characterise their SiO emission. 


We cover H13CO+(1-0),  and SiO(2-1) in baseband-1 with two units of 202 km/s width and a spectral resolution of 0.2 km/s (H13CO+) and 0.4 km/s (SiO). Although SiO is broad towrdas YSOs we are also interested in spread narrow (1-2 km/s) SiO emission and therefore need high spectral resolution also for this line.

In baseband-2 we have two spectral windows of 194 km/s (HCO+) and 197 km/s (HNC) with delta_v=0.4 and 0.2 km/s.

In baseband-3 we have one spectral window for HN13C with 202 km/s with a spectral resolution of 0.1 km/s to investigate in detail the kinematics of the ridge.

In baseband-4 we have one unit deticated to the continuum, with 6395 km/s bandwidth. We need a resolution of 6.6 km/s in this band because we expect severe line contamination towards the most massive YSO and we need to remove the line contaminated channels for a correct continuum estimate.

For HCO+(1-0), HNC(1-0) and SiO we expect broad non-Gaussian profiles towards the YSOs and therefore need large bandwidth for their study.


Finally, we want to stress that we are aware that the HNC spectral window may be affected by higher noise level because it is at the edge of the band. However, the line is very strong along the ridge and its detection and study will still be possible. In any case, this is not our main target as the proposed science can be reached also with HCO+, H13CO+, HN13C and SiO. 




</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Spatial resolution: 

The most compact sub-filaments in the 8 micron images are 3.5 arcsec in width and 24 arcsec in length, therefore the required 1.4 arcsec resolution is needed to spatially resolve this kind of structure. Moreover, our source is at a distance of 1 kpc, and we aim to resolve individual envelopes at sizes of some thousands AU. This can be achieved with 1.4 arcsec  angular resolution.




Largest scale: 

We aim to resolve the morphology and the kinematics of converging flows seen in previous MOPRA observations with a beam of 37 arcsec. These data show that the emission is extended. Moreover, we expect that the emission is more extended than the continuum at least in the most active part of the ridge, which hosts a bright extended HII region. The LABOCA 850 micron continuum emission in that region give a size of ~40 arcsec. Therefore  the 7m array and the TP observations are needed for both the continuum and the lines. 

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
